The paper deals with tree representations and their properties, which are fundamental topics in computer science. The use of dualities and the unification of different representations suggest a focus on data structures and algorithms, which are typically covered in the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) sub-category. The paper also discusses the Range Minimum Query problem, which is a classic problem in computational geometry and falls under the cs.CG (Computational Geometry) sub-category. The Minimum Length Interval Query problem is related to information theory and could be classified under cs.IT (Information Theory). Finally, the use of duality and commonalities in recent work suggest a possible connection to discrete mathematics (cs.DM) and machine learning (cs.LG).
